It appears that, since the journaling is metadata only, and the ensurance of
data blocks is ordering only, that is, data block changes which metadata
changes depend on must be fully written to disk first, I believe it is possible
for situations where data blocks have changed yet metadata have failed to (due
to a crash).

Consider the following example where a file originally contains
	I love you. (length = 11)
and is supposed to become, after a write()
	I love your body. (length = 17)
Suppose for the sake of argument that length = 11 is a block boundary,
then the write() will need to
1. override old block
2. allocate a new block and write to it

Suppose both 1 and 2 have happened and it's time for metadata change, but the
system crashed before they were committed.
Then, the file would be left in an inconsistent state of content
	I love your (length = 11)


Since this 1998 paper describes a project in progress, I checked further doc on
ext3. It seems that the paper only describes what later becomes data=ordered.
	Journally of everything, data and metadata is supported by data=journal.
